    "title": "Do You Need a $500/mo AI Visibility Tool, or Just AEO Fundamentals?",
    "description": "Do you need a $500/mo AI visibility tool, or just the AEO fundamentals? A plain look at what to buy first.",
    "body": "If you've started researching answer engine optimization, you've probably run into a wall of pricing pages \u2014 and they're not cheap. Before you sign up for anything, it's worth understanding what these tools actually do, because a lot of them are solving a different problem than the one you might actually have.\n\n## Two Different Jobs, Often Sold as the Same Thing\n\nThere are really two separate things happening in this space, and the pricing pages tend to blur them together:\n\n**Monitoring** \u2014 tracking how often your business gets mentioned or cited across AI engines like ChatGPT, Perplexity, and Google AI Overviews, usually with dashboards, prompt tracking, and sentiment analysis.\n\n**Implementation** \u2014 actually getting your business into a citable, machine-readable state in the first place: visibility files, structured data, FAQ content written the way AI systems pull answers from.\n\nAlmost every tool in the current market is priced as a monitoring tool \u2014 a recurring monthly subscription, billed like software-as-a-service, because that's genuinely what most of them are. That's a completely reasonable thing to pay for *once you're already visible and want to track performance.* It's a much harder thing to justify if you're not showing up in AI answers at all yet, because monitoring something that isn't happening doesn't tell you much.\n\n## What the Monitoring Tools Actually Cost (2026 Pricing)\n\nHere's the current landscape, monthly:\n\n- **Profound** \u2014 Growth $399/mo (3 engines, 100 prompts), Enterprise $2,000\u2013$5,000+/mo\n- **Ahrefs Brand Radar** \u2014 $199/mo per engine, or $699/mo for all 6, plus a required Ahrefs subscription ($129\u2013$449/mo) \u2014 realistically $828\u2013$1,148+/mo\n- **Goodie AI** \u2014 Starter $295/mo, Pro $495/mo, Enterprise custom (eCommerce/AI shopping focus)\n- **SE Visible (SE Ranking)** \u2014 Core $189/mo, Plus $355/mo, Max $519/mo\n- **Peec AI** \u2014 Pro ~$200\u2013241/mo, Advanced ~$495\u2013505/mo, Enterprise custom\n- **Otterly.AI** \u2014 Standard $189/mo, Premium $489/mo, Enterprise custom\n- **Scrunch AI** \u2014 Core $250/mo, Enterprise custom\n- **AthenaHQ** \u2014 Annual plan $95/mo (3,600 credits), Enterprise custom\n- **Writesonic (GEO)** \u2014 Professional $249/mo\n- **Evertune** \u2014 starts at $3,000+/mo\n\nAdd those up over a year and you're looking at anywhere from roughly $1,100 to $60,000+, depending on the tier \u2014 and none of that spend, by itself, makes your website more citable. It just tells you whether it currently is.\n\n## What Implementation Actually Costs\n\nIf what you actually need first is to *become* visible \u2014 not track whether you already are \u2014 that's a different category, and it doesn't need to be a subscription:\n\n- **AE Optimizer** \u2014 starting at $247 one-time. Generates your AI visibility files, structured data, and AI-ready FAQ/Q&A content, and distributes it across a network of platforms AI crawlers already trust.\n- **AIO Visibility Hub** \u2014 $497 one-time, for a more complete AI visibility setup in a single package.\n- **AI Referrals Hub** \u2014 $1,497 one-time, built specifically for attorneys and law firms, where AI-driven referral discoverability carries higher stakes and more competition.\n\nEach of these is a one-time cost to get your foundation in place \u2014 no recurring bill required just to exist correctly in AI search.\n\n## So Which Do You Actually Need?\n\nA simple way to think about it:\n\n**If your business currently isn't showing up in AI Overviews or AI search results at all**, a $500/mo monitoring dashboard is going to confirm what you probably already suspect \u2014 that you're invisible \u2014 without doing anything to fix it. Implementation comes first.\n\n**If you've already got the fundamentals in place** \u2014 structured data, visibility files, FAQ content built for AI systems \u2014 and you want to track how often you're being cited, compare yourself to competitors, or monitor sentiment across engines, that's exactly what the monitoring tools are built for, and the subscription cost starts to make more sense.\n\nMost businesses researching this for the first time are in the first category, not the second \u2014 which means the fundamentals are worth handling before committing to an ongoing monitoring subscription, not after.\n\n## The Bottom Line\n\nBeing invisible to AI search isn't usually a monitoring problem. It's a missing-foundation problem. Get the foundation in place first \u2014 visibility files, structured data, content built for how AI systems actually pull answers \u2014 and worry about tracking performance once there's something worth tracking.",
    "kind": "listicle"
